[1] Russia Federation
Date: March 10, 2012
Source: Regnum Information Agency [In Russian, machine transaction, edited]
http://www.regnum.ru/news/medicine/1507396.html


Measles outbreak has affected 47 regions this year
--------------------------------------------------
Cases of measles have been recorded in 47 regions of Russia so far in 2012. Vaccination has been declared a priority throughout the Rissian Federation for high risk groups (health workers, teachers, students, trade workers, utilities, etc), as well as for nomadic people and migrants.

According to Rospotrebnadzor [the Health and Consumer Protection Agency], the largest number of cases of measles have been recorded in Moscow, St Petersburg, the Volgograd and Moscow Oblasts, and Stavropol Krai. The most affected have been children under one year of age, followed by children in their first years of life. Adults who had not been vaccinated previously have also been severely affected.

The national immunization calendar requires that all children should be vaccinated twice, first at 12 months and again in their 6th year. In addition, it is planned to vaccinate teenagers and adults up to the age of 35 who have no history of previous vaccination, or who have had only a single vaccination.

Measles is an acute viral infectious disease that spreads from person to person by airborne droplets. The disease is characterized by fever, intoxication, inflammation of the mucous membranes of the upper respiratory tract, and a skin rash. In the absence of vacation measles can infect anyone, regardless of age.

